Tapped In: The Evolution of Digitally-Linked Assets

Chris Davis

Aug 27, 2024 ⋅  16 min read

Key Insights

  • In a crowded consumer market, the real battleground for brands is fostering loyalty through meaningful post-sale engagement.
  • Digitally-Linked Assets (“DLAs”) offer a direct channel for ongoing consumer interaction, enabling brands to gather valuable insights and build deeper relationships that drive long-term value.
  • This evolution opens up new market opportunities for crypto-native companies to build the infrastructure to support Web3 DLA-enabled experiences.
  • DLAs are poised to significantly influence the broader crypto ecosystem, driving new forms of value accrual, data generation, and consumer interaction while accelerating growth and experimentation within Web3.

Introduction

In a growing consumer marketplace saturated with brands, the real battle isn't for sales—it's for loyalty. Research from Bain shows that a mere 5% increase in customer retention can increase profits by 25% to 95%. Yet, many brands are losing this war by failing to connect meaningfully after the point of sale. This issue is particularly pressing for product-centric brands that lack ongoing consumer interaction, making it nearly impossible to gather the insights needed to refine engagement strategies and create enduring relationships.


However, legislation out of the EU is inadvertently handing brands a solution. To support the EU's circular economy goals, The European Commission introduced regulations to drive the adoption of Digital Product Passports (“DPPs”) by 2026. Under this legislation, consumer goods sold within the EU must include a physical link—such as NFC chips —connecting them to a digital record of the product's lifecycle. While this may initially appear as a compliance hurdle, it presents a unique opportunity for forward-thinking brands to differentiate themselves in the market.

Blockchain technology, with its inherent transparency and verifiability, is poised to be the ideal backbone for DPPs. Companies like Arianee and Aura Blockchain Consortium are already spearheading tokenized approaches in fashion, linking products to NFTs containing essential product information.

Beyond compliance, integrating Web3 technology and smart contracts unlocks novel post-sale opportunities to build trust, deepen loyalty, and engage consumers with ongoing interactive experiences.

In this report, we’ll dive into the market evolution fueled by digitally-linked assets (“DLAs”), explore the underlying technology that drives this market, examine opportunities DLAs unlock for consumer brands, and assess potential impacts on the broader crypto ecosystem.

Market Overview

Before exploring DLAs' value propositions, we’ll define exactly what a DLA is and give a high-level overview of how this market is evolving.

What is a Digitally-Linked Asset?

The term “phygital” is commonly used in Web3 to describe products that exist in both the digital and physical worlds. This broad term covers various subcategories, from loosely connected phygital experiences like “redeemable” NFTs to more tightly coupled pairings, such as Digital Product Passports.

This report categorizes "phygital" into two high-level categories:

  • Digitally-Linked Assets
    • Assets that have a tangible link (like chips or QR codes) on the physical product, directly connecting it to digital assets, experiences, or information.
    • Examples: Debit cards, 9dcc Collection-01, Chipped Social nails
  • Digitally-Related Assets
    • Assets that have a digital relationship to the physical product but lack a tangible physical link.
    • Examples: KIKI co-creations, Unisocks, e-books

While this report primarily uses the Web3 fashion industry to contextualize DLAs, DLAs span a wide range of consumer verticals, and virtually any physical product has the potential to be converted into a DLA.

Market Evolution

Giving physical products a digital life creates a paradigm shift in how brands develop post-purchase strategies. DLAs provide a direct line of distribution intrinsically connected to the product owner. Through DLAs, brands can leverage this novel distribution channel to engage with consumers, reward loyalty, and forge deeper, more meaningful relationships.

Additionally, DLAs build their own verifiable onchain history based on real-world interactions and experiences. This ongoing recorded history provides brands with an unprecedented amount of post-purchase consumer data. With this data, brands can refine engagement strategies to improve retention and increase the lifetime value of customers.

This evolution of the post-sale consumer experience creates a market opportunity for crypto-native companies to develop the hardware and software systems that brands can leverage to create and distribute experiences directly to consumers. Below we’ll explore the different layers that make up this market and how they interact with each other to form DLA experiences.

The DLA Stack

At a high level, the DLA stack can be divided into three layers: Infrastructure, Utility, and Brands & IP.

The Infrastructure Layer

The infrastructure supporting Web3 DLAs is comprised of chip-based hardware, software, token standards, registries, and protocols. Together, these components create a foundational layer that enables brands to build DLA experiences for product owners.

Hardware

The hardware component embedded directly into the physical product serves as the link to the product’s digital record. This record can be in the form of an NFT or, in the case of HaLo chips, a fully onchain identity with signing capabilities.

The two chip types most commonly used in Web3 DLAs are near-field communication (“NFC”) chips and hardware-locked smart contract (“HaLo”) chips.

NFC technology facilitates short-range data exchange between devices. NFC chip readers are commonly embedded in smartphones, payment terminals, and ticket machines, enabling them to interact with other NFC-enabled devices to read and write data.

HaLo chips, created by ARX, introduce Web3 features that enhance standard NFC-chip capabilities. HaLo chips self-generate keypairs at the time of manufacturing and can be used to generate signatures like standard crypto wallets do. This allows for a more decentralized product and cuts out any reliance on centralized servers. These chips are compatible with standard NFC technology and can be accessed through NFC readers. At about $49 per chip, ARX’s chips come at a significant price markup when compared to NFC chips issued by companies like IYK, which cost as low as $2 per chip.

Software Services

DLA experiences are made possible by linking the hardware component to a programmable layer of software tools. B2B SaaS services provided by companies such as IYK offer a system with modules that brands can use to configure and manage digital experiences.

When an NFC chip is programmed through IYK, an NFT tied to the physical product is issued. This NFT can only be transferred by tapping the chip, ensuring it stays linked to the physical product. The NFT can unlock various experiences and rewards, such as tickets to events, product discounts, and access to third-party token-gated platforms where customers can view exclusive content.

These platforms also often provide post-sale tooling, like analytics on chip taps, for brands to gather data on real-world interactions with the product. Later in the report, we’ll explore how brands can leverage this data to create increasingly engaging experiences and drive growth.

Over the past few years, market positioning in the DLA software space has begun to take shape. Aura Blockchain Consortium, a non-profit formed by global luxury leaders including LVMH, has established a dominant presence in the high-end luxury goods market. Meanwhile, crypto-native companies like IYK have focused primarily on serving boutique brands, NFT collections, and individual creators.

Standards and Registries

In addition to common token standards like ERC-721, Web3 DLAs may utilize various lesser-known blockchain primitives to enable more dynamic functionality.

  • Ethereum Reality Service (“ERS”): The ERS is a network of registries open to chip manufacturers, creators, and end users that attest to the functions and properties of the chips.
  • Physical-Backed Tokens (“PBT”): An open-source token standard based on ERC-721 created by the Azuki team that integrates with HaLo chips. With asymmetric encryption for proof of ownership, PBTs can be authenticated without APIs from a third party.
  • Token-Bound Accounts (“TBA”): Smart contract accounts that are tied to ERC-721s, giving NFTs the ability to custody assets and execute functions.

Token-bound accounts are an exceptionally effective primitive for driving value accrual to DLAs. By using TBAs, physical products can accumulate value through the digital assets they collect over time. For example, MNTGE, a vintage clothing marketplace, uses TBAs to give their merchandise a way to store NFTs from third-party DLA-enabled patches that can be sewn into the “base garment.” These patches can be tapped like any other DLA, unlocking digital experiences enabled by the patch.

Token-bound accounts also create dynamic secondary markets for DLAs, as the digital value held in the TBA can influence its resale price. For example, just as a baseball signed by an all-star pitcher would resell for much more than an unsigned baseball, a valuable digital signature held in the product’s TBA, acquired through real-world interaction, can impact its resale value.

Utility Layer

At the utility layer, protocols and applications can be integrated into experiences to extend the functionality of DLAs. The two primary use cases we’ve seen so far are token-gated experiences and enhanced real-world social interactions.

Token-Gated Experiences

Platforms like Collab.Land, and Unlock allow brands to create custom token-gating logic based on ownership of specific assets. In combination with DLAs brands can use these platforms to token-gate perks, communities, and events for product owners.

Social Interactions

The Proof-of-Attendance Protocol (“POAP”) enables real-world interactions to be minted as NFTs. In conjunction with DLAs, POAP turns chipped merchandise into a distribution tool for Web3 identities. Paired with Ethereum Name Service (“ENS”), DLA owners can build a digital contact list of people they have connected with in person.

Brands & IP

As the DLA market has evolved, creators at all levels, both in Web2 as well as Web3, have begun leveraging DLA technology. In Web2, we’ve seen mainstream brands like Prada and Nike use DLAs to provide verifiability to the authenticity of products, and musicians like VÉRITÉ and Grimes use DLAs to engage with fans who buy their merchandise. In Web3, NFT communities like Azuki and Pudgy Penguins have leveraged DLAs in limited-edition product runs, and crypto-native fashion brands like 9dcc and MNTGE incorporate DLAs into all of their garments.

To demonstrate how brands implement DLA features, let’s explore how the crypto-native luxury house 9dcc has pushed the boundaries of Web3 consumer engagement with DLAs.

9dcc Luxury DLAs

Founded in 2022 by gmoney, 9dcc is a leader in experimental DLA consumer experiences. At Miami ArtBasel in December 2022, 9dcc set up an in-person event in partnership with ArtBlocks to generate remixes of the iconic Chromie Squiggle by Snowfro in real-time and print the images directly onto t-shirts embedded with NFC chips. gmoney used the token-gating platform Tokenproof to sell Proof-of-Mint NFTs in advance, with each NFT assigned a mint number corresponding to a unique NFT generated at the event. This feature allowed collectors who couldn't attend the in-person event to purchase a shirt that could be redeemed online after the event.

At the event, the Chromie Squiggle was remixed over 1000 times, with each holder receiving an NFT representing the unique one-of-one physical 9dcc shirt featuring their newly minted NFT printed on the garment. To promote ongoing engagement, every shirt is loaded each quarter with 200 POAPs for owners to distribute at events.

The Value of DLAs

DLAs provide brands with a blank canvas to paint digital experiences. These experiences range from core product information to co-creating a digital life that evolves throughout the product’s lifecycle. The design space for curated experiences is vast, and it’s helpful to frame the value propositions of DLAs within a hierarchical structure, where each layer unlocks increasing consumer value.

The hierarchy of value unlocked by DLAs starts with a foundational layer of core product information and extends upward to more interactive consumer experiences that progressively deepen relationships between consumers and brands.

Core Product Information

This foundational layer of the pyramid can be seen as the "regulatory baseline" that will be mandated under Digital Product Passport legislation. At this level, the primary value provided to consumers lies in verifying product authenticity.

Verifying authenticity is crucial for building brand reputation, particularly in industries like luxury fashion, where consumers place a high premium on trust and transparency. According to a report released by the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office (USPTO), international sales of counterfeit and pirated goods total an estimated $1.7 trillion and $4.5 trillion annually. Additionally, ​​IP and brand protection company IncoPro found that 52% of consumers lost trust in a brand after purchasing a fake good online.

At this foundational level, blockchain integrations increase trust through the verifiability derived from inherent features of transparency, immutability, provenance, and decentralization.

Storytelling Through Content

Social media has allowed brands to reach a larger audience than ever before. However, the challenge is that the audience is generalized and cannot be segmented by product ownership. With potentially millions of consumers at different stages in their relationship with the brand, building direct, personalized relationships is nearly impossible through this medium.

DLAs offer a direct distribution channel to connect with product owners, enabling brands to create targeted stories that deepen the consumer’s connection to both the product and the brand. For a fashion brand, this could include interviews with the designer, behind-the-scenes production videos, the history of a product line, or photos of the product on the runway.

By integrating Web3 into the storytelling experience, this content can be distributed as NFTs and owned by the consumer. This dual ownership—of both the physical product and individual elements of its story—creates a deeper emotional connection where the brand's identity becomes intertwined with the consumer's own identity.

Distribution of Value

At this level, brands begin to develop an interactive relationship with consumers. The direct distribution channel provided by DLAs allows brands to reward product owners with perks like exclusive content and experiences, tokens and NFTs, and loyalty points for future rewards.

Beyond incentivizing engagement, introducing ongoing rewards adds an exclusivity or scarcity premium to the product. This added value can justify increasing margins on DLAs. For instance, indie artist VÉRITÉ released a merchandise line embedded with IYK-powered chips, offering exclusive content to her followers before making it available to the public. Despite a 250% price markup on the merchandise, her sales increased by 15%.

Value distribution can also help drive demand for future product releases. In April 2023, when Solana Mobile launched their first Saga mobile phone, they included a $10 airdrop of the memecoin $BONK. Initially, demand for the phone was lackluster, leading the company to slash prices from $1,000 to $599 within four months. In December 2023, $BONK experienced a dramatic price surge, leading to a 10x increase in phone sales within 48 hours. In a week’s time, the phones were sold out.

Each Solana phone came with a soul-bound NFT, making it easy for projects to aggregate addresses for airdrops. In the following months, Solana phone holders received airdrops from dozens of memecoin and NFT projects, yielding returns far exceeding the original purchase price of the phone. When Solana released their second edition phone, speculation on future value led to 30,000 product pre-orders within the first 48 hours, generating $13.5 million in revenue.

Interactive Consumer-Brand Experiences

The top level of the value stack focuses on leveraging interactive experiences to craft a unique, continuous story that unfolds throughout the entire product lifecycle.

Real-world interactions with DLAs, such as tapping chipped merchandise on NFC-readers at events or digitally signing someone’s jacket, bring the physical world onchain. These interactions add to an ongoing historical record of the product’s journey. With consumer engagement data, brands can further individualize rewards. For example, a musician could send afterparty passes to fans who met up during a pre-concert event, plan tour dates in locations their most dedicated fans vote for, or form a group of super fans from all over the world to co-create merchandise.

DLAs also enable time-sensitive interactions. For example, in 9dcc’s collaboration with Internet Game, 9dcc product owners who tapped their merchandise within a 12-hour window unlocked a gaming experience where they competed to earn network points, 9dcc’s form of loyalty rewards.

Flywheel Effects

Interactions with DLAs enable brands to collect valuable real-world interaction and ownership data which can kick off a data-revenue flywheel. Brands can use post-sale data to craft higher-quality consumer experiences that lead to heightened consumer engagement. Product owners then earn rewards, such as loyalty points or tokens, based on their digital and physical engagement. This value can then be funneled into digital or physical purchases, driving additional revenue and producing more data.

Impacts of DLAs on The Broader Crypto Ecosystem

NFTs

Unlike traditional product brands venturing into digital experiences, NFT projects originating in the digital world can create physical products that tie back into their existing digital ecosystems. While many NFT projects have suffered from decreasing secondary sales revenues since their peak in 2021, DLAs offer resilient brands a distribution channel to expand their IP into new verticals.

One of the most notable implementations of a DLA-based strategy was Pudgy Penguins’ recent pivot into gaming. In 2023, they launched Pudgy Toys, a DLA toy line that linked each toy to an NFT character in their flagship Web3 game, Pudgy World. Since its launch, Pudgy Toys has generated over $10 million in revenue and sits on the shelves of major retailers like Walmart and Target. By using their toy line to introduce Pudgy World, Pudgy Penguins were able to onboard toy owners directly into the game and transform what would have been a fragmented offering into a unified, focused consumer experience.

As more NFT projects begin to leverage their IP across multiple verticals - like we are seeing from Doodles and Azuki - we expect that crypto-native infrastructure companies like IYK will see increased demand.

Decentralized Social

Just as Decentralized Social (“DeSoc”) protocols generate evolving social graphs from digital interactions, DLAs generate social graphs based on physical interactions. Pairing DLAs with DeSoc can unify these two graphs, forming a more holistic digital representation of identity.

Chipped Social is a leading crypto-native consumer company building this future. Chipped began its journey producing NFC-chipped press-on nails, enabling a “one-click” experience where consumers can share links and log connections through their Chipped Social app by simply tapping their nail on a phone.

As the product gained traction, Chipped built out its DeSoc aggregation protocol, Gossip Protocol. Gossip Protocol is a decentralized identity and social profile aggregator enabling users to integrate Web3 identities, like Ethereum Name Service (“ENS”), and other crypto-native social platforms like Zora, Hey, and Farcaster, with traditional Web2 profiles such as Twitter, Instagram, and TikTok. When users meet up in person and exchange taps with NFC-enabled devices, Gossip Protocol creates a connection between their digital identities, enabling users to automatically follow each other on any of the aggregated networks.

Connecting users in this way creates large quantities of nuanced social data, which can be used by third parties in their go-to-market. By leveraging this data, applications can target incentives toward cohorts of users who have the strongest connections in both the digital and physical worlds. Similar to how Solana projects sent targeted rewards to Saga holders, applications can provide incentives for tightly-knit communities with shared interests.

Conclusion

As the world moves towards digital ownership, brands and creators that integrate Web3 technology are able to get a head start on developing consumer experiences that deepen the relationships they have with their community. Due to the legislative tailwinds from the EU and adoption from mainstream Web2 brands, we believe DLAs will increasingly become a core part of post-purchase strategies within the consumer sector. As more crypto-native consumer brands adopt this technology, we believe this implementation will accelerate novel experimentation around DLAs within the greater Web3 ecosystem.
